items.title: Show traceback in raise_error when another exception is raised
not_to(equal) using == and not !=
items.body:
When using the matcher equal with a not, (e.g `expect(some_object).not_to(equal(another_object))` first the equal is performed with the `==` operator and then the result is operated with a boolean not. Internally this will call the `__eq__` method on the object to perform the comparison. However, when comparing two objects for inequality in Python with the `!=` operator, the method that will be called is `__ne__`. For most of the cases, this is ok, as `__ne__` will probably be calling `__eq__` (or maybe not, but anyway `not ==` should be equivalent to `!=` if the world made sense at all!).

This is not a big deal by itself, but sometimes one would expect a different behaviour of `not_to(equal())` than the current one. For example, if you're TDDing the `__eq__` and `__ne__` methods of a class (this just happened to me :D).

I am not sure whether making `not_to(equal)` use the `!=` operator would be easy to implement or even would make sense at all but, if not, maybe having another matcher called `different` or `unequal` that actually performed the comparison with `!=` could fit.

If you think this could be of some value I would be glad to help implementing it.

Anyway, I would like to thank you for this great library!

items.title: Allow set with contain matcher
items.body:
Based on #36 the following should be possible:

``` python
expect(set([1, 2, 3])).to(contain(1))
```

items.title: Python's “is” operator behaves unexpectedly with integers, floats...
items.body:
Please see: http://stackoverflow.com/questions/306313/pythons-is-operator-behaves-unexpectedly-with-integers

An example:

``` python
a = 255
b = 255
a is b
True

a = 257
b = 257
a is b
False
```

Also you can try doing `id()` for integers <= 256 and every time is the same id for integer, but when numbers is greater than 256 the id is changing every time.

For floats every time is different

items.title: Improve failure messages
items.body:
I was looking at how other libraries report failure messages.

For example,

pyhamcrest:

``` python
assert_that({'foo': 1}, has_key('bar'))
```

``` python-traceback
Expected: a dictionary containing key 'bar'
     but: was <{'foo': 1}>
```

rspec:

``` ruby
expect({:foo => 1}).to have_key(:bar)
```

```
expected #has_key?(:bar) to return true, got false
```

items.title: Fix failure message when composing have_key/have_keys matcher
items.body:
The `have_key` and `have_keys` assertions are affected.

If you run

``` python
expect({}).to(have_key('foo', 1))
```

you get the following failure message:

``` python-traceback
AssertionError: Expected {} to have key 'foo' equal 1
```

But if you use the `have_key` matcher as an argument to another matcher:

``` python
expect([{}]).to(contain(have_key('foo', 1)))
```

The failure message now is wrong:

``` python-traceback
AssertionError: Expected [{}] to contain have keys 'foo' equal 1 but is not a dict
```

items.title: Add a way to assert a string is contained into antoher
Add only.have.key/keys expectation
items.body:
The idea is to add the same behavior added at 6c45d75f84f91ac991f3f9ff002cda17077b0e73 and allow to expect that a dict only has the given keys.

For example:

``` python
expect({'foo': 1}).to.only.have.key('foo')
```

items.title: have.key passes if actual is an iterable containing expected key
items.body:
The following example reproduces de error:

``` python
expect('very large string ...').to.have.keys('very', 'str')
```

This behavior is caused by this line: https://github.com/jaimegildesagredo/expects/blob/master/expects/expectations.py#L152

I think it should be replaced by

``` python
name in self.actual.keys()
```

items.title: Error in `to.have` when items are dicts
items.body:
When expecting a list or iterable of dicts to have some item I get the following error:

``` python
>>> expect([{'foo': 1}, {'bar': 2}]).to.have({'foo': 1}, {'bar': 3})
Traceback (most recent call last):
  File "/usr/local/lib/python2.7/dist-packages/expects/expectations.py", line 107, in __call__
    collection = self.actual if len(args) == 1 else set(self.actual)
TypeError: unhashable type: 'dict'
```

This error comes from #6, where it was used a `set` to consume an iterable before check for items in it, but `set` items must be hasable ones and `dicts` aren't. So, I think we should use a `list` here istead of a `set`.
